219 /*
220 Perform OR operation on 2 index_merge lists, storing result in first list.
221
222 NOTES
223 The following conversion is implemented:
224 (a_1 &&...&& a_N)||(b_1 &&...&& b_K) = AND_i,j(a_i || b_j) =>
225 => (a_1||b_1).
226
227 i.e. all conjuncts except the first one are currently dropped.
228 This is done to avoid producing N*K ways to do index_merge.
229
230 If (a_1||b_1) produce a condition that is always true, NULL is returned
231 and index_merge is discarded (while it is actually possible to try
232 harder).
233
234 As a consequence of this, choice of keys to do index_merge read may depend
235 on the order of conditions in WHERE part of the query.
236
237 RETURN
238 0 OK, result is stored in *im1
239 other Error, both passed lists are unusable
240 */

246 43 im1->push_back(imerge);
247
248 43 return imerge->or_sel_imerge_with_checks(param, remove_jump_scans,
249 43 im2->head());
250 }

610 /*
611 Remove the trees that are not suitable for record retrieval.
612 SYNOPSIS
613 param Range analysis parameter
614 tree Tree to be processed, tree->type is KEY
615
616 DESCRIPTION
617 This function walks through tree->keys[] and removes the SEL_ARG* trees
618 that are not "maybe" trees (*) and cannot be used to construct quick range
619 selects.
620 (*) - have type MAYBE or MAYBE_KEY. Perhaps we should remove trees of
621 these types here as well.
622
623 A SEL_ARG* tree cannot be used to construct quick select if it has
624 tree->part != 0. (e.g. it could represent "keypart2 < const").
625
626 WHY THIS FUNCTION IS NEEDED
627
628 Normally we allow construction of SEL_TREE objects that have SEL_ARG
629 trees that do not allow quick range select construction. For example for
630 " keypart1=1 AND keypart2=2 " the execution will proceed as follows:
631 tree1= SEL_TREE { SEL_ARG{keypart1=1} }
632 tree2= SEL_TREE { SEL_ARG{keypart2=2} } -- can't make quick range select
633 from this
634 call tree_and(tree1, tree2) -- this joins SEL_ARGs into a usable SEL_ARG
635 tree.
636
637 There is an exception though: when we construct index_merge SEL_TREE,
638 any SEL_ARG* tree that cannot be used to construct quick range select can
639 be removed, because current range analysis code doesn't provide any way
640 that tree could be later combined with another tree.
641 Consider an example: we should not construct
642 st1 = SEL_TREE {
643 merges = SEL_IMERGE {
644 SEL_TREE(t.key1part1 = 1),
645 SEL_TREE(t.key2part2 = 2) -- (*)
646 }
647 };
648 because
649 - (*) cannot be used to construct quick range select,
650 - There is no execution path that would cause (*) to be converted to
651 a tree that could be used.
652
653 The latter is easy to verify: first, notice that the only way to convert
654 (*) into a usable tree is to call tree_and(something, (*)).
655
656 Second look at what tree_and/tree_or function would do when passed a
657 SEL_TREE that has the structure like st1 tree has, and conclude that
658 tree_and(something, (*)) will not be called.
659
660 RETURN
661 0 Ok, some suitable trees left
662 1 No tree->keys[] left.
663 */

1007 /**
1008 Combine two range expression under a common OR. On a logical level, the
1009 transformation is key_or( expr1, expr2 ) => expr1 OR expr2.
1010
1011 Both expressions are assumed to be in the SEL_ARG format. In a logic sense,
1012 the format is reminiscent of DNF, since an expression such as the following
1013
1014 ( 1 < kp1 < 10 AND p1 ) OR ( 10 <= kp2 < 20 AND p2 )
1015
1016 where there is a key consisting of keyparts ( kp1, kp2, ..., kpn ) and p1
1017 and p2 are valid SEL_ARG expressions over keyparts kp2 ... kpn, is a valid
1018 SEL_ARG condition. The disjuncts appear ordered by the minimum endpoint of
1019 the first range and ranges must not overlap. It follows that they are also
1020 ordered by maximum endpoints. Thus
1021
1022 ( 1 < kp1 <= 2 AND ( kp2 = 2 OR kp2 = 3 ) ) OR kp1 = 3
1023
1024 Is a a valid SER_ARG expression for a key of at least 2 keyparts.
1025
1026 For simplicity, we will assume that expr2 is a single range predicate,
1027 i.e. on the form ( a < x < b AND ... ). It is easy to generalize to a
1028 disjunction of several predicates by subsequently call key_or for each
1029 disjunct.
1030
1031 The algorithm iterates over each disjunct of expr1, and for each disjunct
1032 where the first keypart's range overlaps with the first keypart's range in
1033 expr2:
1034
1035 If the predicates are equal for the rest of the keyparts, or if there are
1036 no more, the range in expr2 has its endpoints copied in, and the SEL_ARG
1037 node in expr2 is deallocated. If more ranges became connected in expr1, the
1038 surplus is also dealocated. If they differ, two ranges are created.
1039
1040 - The range leading up to the overlap. Empty if endpoints are equal.
1041
1042 - The overlapping sub-range. May be the entire range if they are equal.
1043
1044 Finally, there may be one more range if expr2's first keypart's range has a
1045 greater maximum endpoint than the last range in expr1.
1046
1047 For the overlapping sub-range, we recursively call key_or. Thus in order to
1048 compute key_or of
1049
1050 (1) ( 1 < kp1 < 10 AND 1 < kp2 < 10 )
1051
1052 (2) ( 2 < kp1 < 20 AND 4 < kp2 < 20 )
1053
1054 We create the ranges 1 < kp <= 2, 2 < kp1 < 10, 10 <= kp1 < 20. For the
1055 first one, we simply hook on the condition for the second keypart from (1)
1056 : 1 < kp2 < 10. For the second range 2 < kp1 < 10, key_or( 1 < kp2 < 10, 4
1057 < kp2 < 20 ) is called, yielding 1 < kp2 < 20. For the last range, we reuse
1058 the range 4 < kp2 < 20 from (2) for the second keypart. The result is thus
1059
1060 ( 1 < kp1 <= 2 AND 1 < kp2 < 10 ) OR
1061 ( 2 < kp1 < 10 AND 1 < kp2 < 20 ) OR
1062 ( 10 <= kp1 < 20 AND 4 < kp2 < 20 )
1063
1064 key_or() does not modify key1 nor key2 if they are in use by other roots
1065 (although typical use is that key1 has been disconnected from its root
1066 and thus can be modified in-place). Thus, it does not change their
1067 use_count.
1068
1069 The returned node will not have its use_count increased; you are supposed
1070 to do that yourself when you connect it to a root.
